Europe
---
[2] UK: Public Health England
Date: Tue 18 Feb 2020
Source: Cheshire East Council [abridged, edited]
https://www.cheshireeast.gov.uk/council_and_democracy/council_information/media_hub/media_releases/18022020-an-increase-in-the-cases-of-mumps-in-england.aspx


Our Public Health team is recommending that children and young people who may have missed out on protection from mumps should receive a catch-up MMR vaccination. In England there has been a significant rise in the number of cases of mumps [in the past year].

The latest data from Public Health England (PHE) show that there were 5042 lab-confirmed cases of mumps in England in 2019 compared with 1066 cases in 2018. This is the highest number of cases since 2009.

The steep rise in cases in 2019 has been largely driven by outbreaks in universities and colleges. Many of the cases in 2019 were young adults born in the late 1990s and early 2000s who missed out on the MMR vaccine when they were children.

In Cheshire East, our uptake was less than 80% for the 2nd dose in the early 2000s, more than 15% below the figure required for group immunity. These cohorts are now old enough to attend college and university and are likely to continue fuelling outbreaks into 2020.

Mumps is a viral illness caused by a paramyxovirus. Mumps can be caught through direct contact with saliva or droplets from the saliva of an infected person.

[MMR vaccine] uptake has improved locally in recent years with most practices achieving between 90% and 95% for the 1st dose; however, in some towns there are still more than 10% of children who have not had both doses of MMR before they start school.

